# 2026-06-05 — Deploy config simplification (Lakebase)

## Collapse Lakebase deploy config to its irreducible surface

**Context:** The Lakebase block in `scripts/deploy.config.sh` carried three
layers, two of which were pure pass-through indirection. The Graph DB
"separate instance" variables (`LAKEBASE_GRAPH_PROJECT/_BRANCH/_DATABASE`)
all defaulted to empty and were resolved back to the registry values in
`deploy.sh` — a hypothetical layout that was never used, since the graph DB,
sync tables, and registry always co-locate in the same Lakebase
project/branch/database and differ only by Postgres schema. The
`LAKEBASE_BOOTSTRAP_INSTANCE/_BRANCH/_SCHEMA` variables were likewise aliases
of `LAKEBASE_PROJECT` / `LAKEBASE_BRANCH` / `LAKEBASE_REGISTRY_SCHEMA`. Only
the Postgres datname was genuinely distinct. The mandatory Lakebase config
surface drops from 13 variables to 7.

**Changes:**

1. `scripts/deploy.config.sh` — removed `DEFAULT_LAKEBASE_BOOTSTRAP_DATABASE`,
   `DEFAULT_LAKEBASE_GRAPH_PROJECT/_BRANCH/_DATABASE` and the
   `LAKEBASE_BOOTSTRAP_INSTANCE/_BRANCH/_DATABASE/_SCHEMA` +
   `LAKEBASE_GRAPH_PROJECT/_BRANCH/_DATABASE` exports. Renamed the datname to
   `LAKEBASE_DATABASE` (moved into section 3 beside the other core Lakebase
   vars). Section 3b now only declares `LAKEBASE_GRAPH_SCHEMA` +
   `LAKEBASE_SYNC_SCHEMA`. `APP_LAKEBASE_DATABASE` now tracks `LAKEBASE_DATABASE`.
2. `scripts/deploy.sh` — registry/graph/sync grant calls now pass
   `-i $LAKEBASE_PROJECT -b $LAKEBASE_BRANCH -d $LAKEBASE_DATABASE` directly and
   vary only `-s` per schema; dropped the `_GRAPH_INSTANCE/_BRANCH/_DATABASE`
   resolution block and updated the error-guidance echo + a stale comment.
3. `Makefile` — `bootstrap-lakebase` target uses the core vars instead of the
   removed `LAKEBASE_BOOTSTRAP_*` aliases.
4. `scripts/bootstrap-lakebase-perms.sh` — rewrote the three-schema header
   comment block to reflect the same-instance model; dropped the
   "different instance" subsection and example.
5. `scripts/migrate-registry-to-lakebase.sh` — updated the env fallbacks from
   `LAKEBASE_BOOTSTRAP_*` to `LAKEBASE_REGISTRY_SCHEMA` / `LAKEBASE_DATABASE` /
   `LAKEBASE_PROJECT` / `LAKEBASE_BRANCH`.
6. `README.md`, `docs/deployment.md` — renamed the deploy-config variable
   references in the three-schema tables and removed the "separate Lakebase
   instance" guidance.

**Compatibility note:** Anyone exporting `LAKEBASE_BOOTSTRAP_DATABASE` (or the
other removed `LAKEBASE_BOOTSTRAP_*` / `LAKEBASE_GRAPH_*` vars) in their
env/CI loses that override silently — set `LAKEBASE_DATABASE` instead. The
legacy `databricks_postgres` datname guidance survives, now via
`LAKEBASE_DATABASE=databricks_postgres`. Capability removed: pinning the graph
DB to a different Lakebase instance than the registry (never realistic given
synced-table co-location requirements).

**Modified files:**
- `scripts/deploy.config.sh`
- `scripts/deploy.sh`
- `Makefile`
- `scripts/bootstrap-lakebase-perms.sh`
- `scripts/migrate-registry-to-lakebase.sh`
- `README.md`
- `docs/deployment.md`

**Test result:** No Python touched. `bash -n` passes on all 4 modified shell
scripts; sourcing `deploy.config.sh` resolves the new `LAKEBASE_DATABASE` /
`APP_LAKEBASE_DATABASE` correctly and leaves the removed vars unset. Full
`pytest` suite re-run (see session) — pre-existing `tests/property/*`
collection errors from the missing optional `hypothesis` dev dependency are
unrelated to this change.

## Section-4 fallbacks track section-3 bound values

**Context:** The `app.yaml` runtime fallbacks (section 4 of
`deploy.config.sh`) carried their own `DEFAULT_APP_*` literals for the
registry triplet and the DBSQL warehouse, which had silently drifted from
the section-3 bound values (e.g. fallback registry `benoit_cayla.ontobricks.
OntoBricksRegistry` vs bound `benoit_cayla.ontobricks_demo.registry`; fallback
warehouse `66e8366e84d57752` vs bound `d2096aa075ad44a3`). Since these are
only consulted on the unbound path (local dev / MCP), the divergence was a
latent footgun. Map them onto the section-3 values so the unbound path uses
the same target you actually deploy.

**Changes:**

1. `scripts/deploy.config.sh` — removed `DEFAULT_APP_SQL_WAREHOUSE_FALLBACK`,
   `DEFAULT_APP_REGISTRY_CATALOG/_SCHEMA/_VOLUME`. `APP_SQL_WAREHOUSE_FALLBACK`
   now defaults to `$WAREHOUSE_ID`; `APP_REGISTRY_CATALOG/_SCHEMA/_VOLUME`
   default to `$REGISTRY_CATALOG/_SCHEMA/_VOLUME`. All remain env-overridable.
2. `scripts/deploy.config.sh` — `APP_TRIPLESTORE_TABLE` now composes its
   catalog.schema from `REGISTRY_CATALOG.REGISTRY_SCHEMA`; only the table name
   (`DEFAULT_APP_TRIPLESTORE_TABLE_NAME=default_triplestore`) stays a literal.
   Was hard-coded `benoit_cayla.ontobricks.default_triplestore`, now resolves
   to `benoit_cayla.ontobricks_demo.default_triplestore`.
   Left independent: `DEFAULT_APP_MLFLOW_TRACKING_URI` — no section-3 counterpart.

**Modified files:**
- `scripts/deploy.config.sh`

**Test result:** Verified in a clean `env -i` subshell — `APP_SQL_WAREHOUSE_
FALLBACK` now equals `WAREHOUSE_ID` and the `APP_REGISTRY_*` fallbacks equal
the bound `REGISTRY_*`. `bash -n` passes.

