## Harden deploy.sh error handling

**Context:** `scripts/deploy.sh` relied on `set -euo pipefail` alone — a
failure mid-deploy aborted with no indication of which step broke or why, and
there were no preflight guards, so a missing tool / empty config value / wrong
target only surfaced as an opaque Databricks CLI error (or a partial deploy).

**Changes:**

1. `scripts/deploy.sh` — added colourised step logging (`begin_step` / `info`
   / `ok` / `warn` / `die`, TTY-aware so CI logs stay plain) and an `ERR` trap
   (`_on_error`) that prints the failing step name, the exact `BASH_COMMAND`,
   the `deploy.sh:<line>`, the exit code, and a step-specific hint.
2. New **Preflight** step (runs before any API call): asserts required tooling
   (`databricks`, `python3`, with CLI-version display), required files
   (`databricks.yml`, `app.yaml.template`, renderer, bootstrap scripts — only
   those the chosen flags will use), and non-empty required config values
   (`APP_NAME`, `WAREHOUSE_ID`, `REGISTRY_*`, and on a Lakebase target
   `LAKEBASE_*`). Warns when `LAKEBASE_DATABASE_RESOURCE_SEGMENT` is not a
   `db-…` id, and when the target is not one of the documented values.
3. Auth verification promoted to its own early step with a fail-fast `die` +
   login hint; username resolution made tolerant.
4. Render / Validate / Deploy / Run each wrapped with a `die` carrying a
   tailored remediation hint; render now asserts `app.yaml` was produced.
5. Verify / self-permission / Lakebase-grant steps converted to the new
   helpers; self-permission failure now warns with a `make bootstrap-perms`
   pointer instead of being silently swallowed. Replaced ad-hoc
   `[[ $TARGET == *lakebase* ]]` checks with a single `IS_LAKEBASE` flag.
6. Updated the header docstring (9-step flow) and the `--help` line range.

**Modified files:**
- `scripts/deploy.sh`

**Test result:** `bash -n` passes. `--help` renders the new flow. Verified the
guards abort cleanly before any API call: unknown option → `die`; missing
`databricks` on PATH → preflight `die` with install hint (exit 1). No real
deploy executed.

## Add --dry-run + resource existence checks to deploy.sh

**Context:** Follow-up to the error-handling work — run *all* checks before
the deploy mutates anything, and add a way to run only the checks.

**Changes:**

1. `scripts/deploy.sh` — new **Resource existence checks** step (after
   validate, before deploy): read-only verification that the upstream
   resources the bundle binds to actually exist — SQL warehouse
   (`databricks warehouses get`), registry Volume (`databricks volumes read`),
   and on a Lakebase target the Postgres database (`databricks postgres
   list-databases` + `db-…` segment match). Soft `warn` on a normal deploy;
   upgraded to a hard `die` under `--dry-run` so a check run is decisive.
2. `scripts/deploy.sh` — new `--dry-run` (alias `--check`) flag: runs
   preflight → auth → render → validate → resource checks, prints a
   `=== Dry run OK ===` summary, and exits 0 **before** deploy. (app.yaml is
   still rendered locally — it is a generated throwaway.)
3. `scripts/deploy.sh` — renumbered the step-comment headers (now 11 steps),
   updated the header docstring + usage + `--help` line range.
4. `Makefile` — new `deploy-dry-run` target (and `.PHONY` + help entry)
   wrapping `scripts/deploy.sh --dry-run`.

**Modified files:**
- `scripts/deploy.sh`
- `Makefile`

**Test result:** `bash -n` passes. Ran `scripts/deploy.sh --dry-run` against
the live workspace end-to-end: preflight + auth (benoit.cayla@databricks.com)
+ render + `bundle validate` + all three resource checks (warehouse, volume,
Lakebase `db-v6vc-8ibz5oeigo`) passed; exited 0 with no remote changes.

## Make deploy registry-scoped: rename datname, drop graph/sync grants

**Context:** Correction to the earlier "same-instance" assumption in this
file. There are only **two** Lakebase schemas (registry + graph — the "sync"
schema is a sub-case of the graph side under `managed_synced`), and they may
live in **different** Lakebase projects: the graph DB is configured in-app
(`Settings → Graph DB` → `graph_engine_config`), not at deploy time. So
`deploy.sh` reaching into the graph/sync schemas with the *registry's*
project/database was unsafe. The deploy script is now strictly
registry-scoped, and the datname variable is renamed to make that explicit.

**Changes:**

1. `scripts/deploy.config.sh` — renamed `LAKEBASE_DATABASE` →
   `LAKEBASE_REGISTRY_DATABASE` (and `DEFAULT_LAKEBASE_DATABASE` →
   `DEFAULT_LAKEBASE_REGISTRY_DATABASE`), symmetric with
   `LAKEBASE_REGISTRY_SCHEMA`. Removed the section-3b `LAKEBASE_GRAPH_SCHEMA` /
   `LAKEBASE_SYNC_SCHEMA` exports entirely. `APP_LAKEBASE_DATABASE` now tracks
   `LAKEBASE_REGISTRY_DATABASE`.
2. `scripts/deploy.sh` — `require_var` and the registry grant use
   `LAKEBASE_REGISTRY_DATABASE`. Removed the graph + sync grant blocks from
   step 11; it now grants the registry schema only, with a comment pointing to
   the in-app "Create graph DB" flow for the graph schema.
3. `Makefile` — `bootstrap-lakebase` uses `LAKEBASE_REGISTRY_DATABASE`.
4. `scripts/migrate-registry-to-lakebase.sh` — datname fallback reads
   `LAKEBASE_REGISTRY_DATABASE` (the app-runtime `LAKEBASE_DATABASE` export it
   emits for the embedded migration is unchanged — that's the Settings
   contract).
5. `scripts/bootstrap-lakebase-perms.sh` — rewrote the header from
   "three same-instance schemas" to a generic per-schema grant tool: registry
   (auto, via deploy.sh) vs graph (in-app / manual, possibly a different
   project).
6. `README.md`, `docs/deployment.md`, `docs/lakebase-graphdb.md` — updated the
   permission-grant tables and variable references to the two-schema,
   registry-scoped model; graph examples now use the graph DB's own
   project/branch/database.

**Compatibility note:** anyone exporting `LAKEBASE_DATABASE`,
`LAKEBASE_GRAPH_SCHEMA`, or `LAKEBASE_SYNC_SCHEMA` to influence the **deploy**
loses that override — set `LAKEBASE_REGISTRY_DATABASE` for the datname, and
grant the graph schema via the in-app flow or a manual
`bootstrap-lakebase-perms.sh` run. The app-runtime `LAKEBASE_DATABASE` env var
(read by `Settings` / `LakebaseAuth`) is unchanged.

**Modified files:**
- `scripts/deploy.config.sh`
- `scripts/deploy.sh`
- `Makefile`
- `scripts/migrate-registry-to-lakebase.sh`
- `scripts/bootstrap-lakebase-perms.sh`
- `README.md`
- `docs/deployment.md`
- `docs/lakebase-graphdb.md`

**Test result:** `bash -n` passes on all 3 modified shell scripts. Sourcing
`deploy.config.sh` in a clean `env -i` subshell resolves
`LAKEBASE_REGISTRY_DATABASE=ontobricks_demo`,
`APP_LAKEBASE_DATABASE=ontobricks_demo`, and leaves `LAKEBASE_GRAPH_SCHEMA`
unset. Repo grep confirms the only remaining `LAKEBASE_DATABASE` references are
the intended app-runtime env var (migrate script export, `src/**`, app.yaml
template, .env/get-started examples).

## Fix: domain_versions.status column missing on upgraded deployments

**Context:** App crashed with `psycopg.errors.UndefinedColumn: column v.status
does not exist` when listing registry domains. The `_ensure_domain_versions_
status_column` self-heal in `store.py` ran an `ALTER TABLE` at runtime but the
app SP doesn't own the tables (owner is `benoit.cayla@databricks.com`), so it
silently swallowed the failure (logged as WARNING) and the SELECT immediately
after hit the missing column.

**Root fix applied directly:** `ALTER TABLE ontobricks_demo.domain_versions ADD
COLUMN IF NOT EXISTS status text NOT NULL DEFAULT 'DRAFT'` + index — run as
the schema owner, column now present, all 8 domain versions defaulted to
`DRAFT`. App immediately usable without redeploy.

**Structural fixes:**

1. `scripts/bootstrap-lakebase-perms.sh` — added Step 2b (between schema-
   exists check and SP grants loop): runs the `status` column migration +
   index as the schema owner. Idempotent (`ADD COLUMN IF NOT EXISTS` /
   `CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS`). Any future `make deploy` or
   `make bootstrap-lakebase` will apply it automatically so upgraded
   deployments never hit this gap again.
2. `src/back/objects/registry/store/lakebase/store.py` —
   `_ensure_domain_versions_status_column` now logs at `ERROR` (not
   `WARNING`) with an actionable hint pointing to `make bootstrap-lakebase`
   when the ALTER fails, so the misconfiguration surfaces in app logs.

**Modified files:**
- `scripts/bootstrap-lakebase-perms.sh`
- `src/back/objects/registry/store/lakebase/store.py`

**Test result:** Column added and verified in Lakebase (`status|text|'DRAFT'::text`).
`bash -n` clean; `import store` clean. Domain listing works in the deployed app.

## Multi-instance deploy: change DEFAULT_APP_NAME only

**Context:** Deploying a second instance previously required manually updating
5 variables (MCP app name, registry schema, Lakebase schema, Lakebase datname,
DAB target). This made the "just spin up a new instance" workflow error-prone.

**Changes:**

1. `scripts/deploy.config.sh` — restructured section 0 into three sub-sections:
   - **0a. Instance identity** — `DEFAULT_APP_NAME` is now THE single line
     to edit. Everything else derives from it.
   - **0b. Workspace constants** — shared across instances (warehouse ID,
     UC catalog, Lakebase project/branch/segment). Set once per workspace.
   - **0b2. Schema name override** — escape hatch (`DEFAULT_SCHEMA_OVERRIDE`)
     for existing deployments whose schema predates the naming convention.
     Set to `""` for new deployments; leave set for legacy ones.
   - **0c. Derived defaults** — auto-computes `DEFAULT_MCP_APP_NAME`,
     `DEFAULT_REGISTRY_SCHEMA`, `DEFAULT_LAKEBASE_REGISTRY_SCHEMA`,
     `DEFAULT_LAKEBASE_REGISTRY_DATABASE` from `DEFAULT_APP_NAME`
     (hyphens → underscores). `DEFAULT_DAB_TARGET` corrected to
     `dev-lakebase` (was wrong `"ontobricks"`).

   Existing deployment (`ontobricks-050` / `ontobricks_demo` schema) continues
   working because `DEFAULT_SCHEMA_OVERRIDE="ontobricks_demo"` is set.
   New instance example: set `DEFAULT_APP_NAME="ontobricks-foo"` and
   `DEFAULT_SCHEMA_OVERRIDE=""` → `APP=ontobricks-foo`,
   `MCP=mcp-ontobricks-foo`, all schemas = `ontobricks_foo`.

**Modified files:**
- `scripts/deploy.config.sh`

**Test result:** Both scenarios verified in `env -i` clean subshell:
existing → `REGISTRY_SCHEMA=ontobricks_demo`; new instance (`ontobricks-foo`,
no override) → all three schema names = `ontobricks_foo`, MCP =
`mcp-ontobricks-foo`.

## Fix: SP permission errors during Digital Twin Build (VIEW + pipeline)

**Context:** After fresh deploy, Digital Twin Build failed with two distinct
permission errors in the `managed_synced` code path:

1. `Permission denied while creating the VIEW … MANAGE on Table
   'benoit_cayla.ontobricks_demo.triplestore_cust360auto_v4'` — triplestore
   views previously created by `benoit.cayla@databricks.com` had
   `owner=unknown`; the SP had `ALL_PRIVILEGES` on the catalog but not
   `MANAGE` on those specific objects, so `CREATE OR REPLACE VIEW` was refused.

2. `User 95084ef9 does not have View permissions on pipeline
   2c552bc9-4131-4998-b2c6-e1b4b46c4bc8` — orphaned Lakeflow synced-table
   pipeline with no valid owner; Databricks refused both PATCH and PUT
   permission updates (requires metastore admin to change owner).

**Immediate fixes applied directly:**
- Dropped 5 `unknown`-owner triplestore views in `ontobricks_demo` (will be
  recreated by the SP on next Build).
- Granted `ALL_PRIVILEGES` on schema `benoit_cayla.ontobricks_demo` to both
  SPs (main + MCP) — includes `MANAGE`, so the SP can now replace any object
  in the schema regardless of original ownership.
- Deleted the orphaned pipeline `2c552bc9` (IDLE, no tables, no owner) — SP
  will recreate it under its own ownership on next Build.

**Structural fix:**
- `scripts/bootstrap-app-permissions.sh` — added a UC schema
  `ALL_PRIVILEGES` step after the self-permission loop. Sources
  `REGISTRY_CATALOG` / `REGISTRY_SCHEMA` from `deploy.config.sh` (or
  `UC_CATALOG` / `UC_SCHEMA` env overrides). Every future `make bootstrap-perms`
  or `make deploy` run will apply this grant, so upgraded deployments and
  new instances both get it automatically.

**Modified files:**
- `scripts/bootstrap-app-permissions.sh`

**Test result:** `bash -n` passes. SP privileges verified:
`ALL_PRIVILEGES` on `benoit_cayla.ontobricks_demo`; orphaned pipeline and
`unknown`-owner views removed. Build retryable immediately.

## Fix: SP lacks USAGE on Lakebase graph schema (managed_synced Build step 5)

**Context:** Build failed at step 5 with `permission denied for schema public
… CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS cust360auto_v4__app`. The SP connected to Lakebase
but had no USAGE on the graph schema `ontobricks_graph_demo2`, so Postgres
fell back to `public` and denied the table creation there too.

Root cause: `bootstrap-lakebase-perms.sh` (called by deploy) only bootstraps
the registry schema. The graph schema lives in the same Lakebase database
(`ontobricks_demo` in `ontobricks-demo2/production`) but needs a separate
bootstrap run — the deploy script intentionally doesn't manage graph grants
since graph may be in a different project. The graph config was found in
`global_config.graph_engine_config`: schema=`ontobricks_graph_demo2`,
database=`ontobricks_demo` (same instance as registry in this deployment).

**Immediate fix:**
- Ran `bootstrap-lakebase-perms.sh -i ontobricks-demo2 -b production
  -d ontobricks_demo -s ontobricks_graph_demo2 -a ontobricks-050
  -a mcp-ontobricks-050` — both SPs got `USAGE + DML` on the graph schema.

**Structural fix:**
- `scripts/bootstrap-lakebase-perms.sh` — Step 2b migration guard now checks
  whether `domain_versions` exists in the target schema before running the
  `ALTER TABLE`. Previously always ran unconditionally, producing a noisy error
  when bootstrapping the graph schema (which has a different table layout).

**Modified files:**
- `scripts/bootstrap-lakebase-perms.sh`

**Test result:** Bootstrap ran cleanly on graph schema — both SPs got
`USAGE + DML`; migration step skipped (no `domain_versions` in graph schema).
`bash -n` passes. Build retryable.

## Side-step app-name collision: new deploy identity (ontobricks-051)

**Context:** `make deploy` failed with "bundle deploy failed … an app name
already owned by another bundle". `ontobricks-050` was already deployed by a
different bundle (must be left untouched). Databricks Apps names are
workspace-global, so a fresh sync folder alone cannot resolve the clash — the
new deployment needs its own app name (binding/taking over the existing app is
not an option here). `databricks.yml` already derives
`workspace.root_path` from `${var.app_name}`, so renaming the app also
isolates the sync/state folder automatically.

**Changes:**

1. `scripts/deploy.config.sh` — `DEFAULT_APP_NAME` `ontobricks-050` →
   `ontobricks-051` (free, verified against `databricks apps list`), and
   `DEFAULT_MCP_APP_NAME` `-05` (invalid — app names cannot start with `-`) →
   `mcp-ontobricks-051`. Added a note that app names are workspace-global and
   the root_path tracks `app_name`.

**Modified files:**
- `scripts/deploy.config.sh`

**Test result:** `databricks bundle validate -t dev-lakebase` (clean `env -i`
subshell) exits 0. Resolved `workspace.root_path =
/Workspace/Users/benoit.cayla@databricks.com/.bundle/ontobricks-051/dev-lakebase`
(distinct folder) and apps `['mcp-ontobricks-051', 'ontobricks-051']` — the
existing `ontobricks-050` is not referenced. Only a benign `htmlcov` sync
exclude warning.

